<p>My goal is to create a simple function that titles a graph with the name of the variable that's been plotted.</p>  <p>So far I have:</p>  <pre><code>def comparigraphside(rawvariable, filtervariable, cut):     variable = rawvariable[filtervariable &gt; 0]     upperbound = np.mean(variable) + 3*np.std(variable)     plt.figure(figsize=(20,5))     plt.subplot(121)     plt.hist(variable[filtervariable &lt;= cut], bins=20, range=(0,upperbound), normed=True)     plt.title("%s customers with filter less than or equal to %s" % (len(variable[filtervariable &lt;= cut]), cut))     plt.subplot(122)     plt.hist(variable[filtervariable &gt; cut], bins=20, range=(0,upperbound), normed=True)     plt.title("%s customers with filter greater than %s" % (len(variable[filtervariable &gt; cut]), cut)); </code></pre>  <p>And where it's:</p>  <pre><code>plt.title("%s customers with filter less/greater...")  </code></pre>  <p>I'd love it to say:</p>  <pre><code>plt.title("%s customers with %s less/greater...") </code></pre>  <p>At the moment the only solution I can think of involves making a dictionary of my variables, which I would like to avoid. Any and all assistance is much appreciated.</p>